text.tspan: Sapropels are dark, organic-rich layers in
sediment on the floor of the Mediterranean
Sea. They seem to represent times of high
discharge from the Nile, and thus times of
high rainfall in Africa. Thus they are
thought to be a good proxy for wet times in
the Sahara. The picture to the right shows
several black sapropels in a 10-m long core
from an Ocean Drilling Project site in the
Eastern Mediterranean. The core has been
cut into 1.5-m segments, laid out side by
side. The yellow numbers correspond to

The history of the Nile appears to have been
very complicated, with different sources at
different times, and intervals in which the river
did not reach Egypt, or did not reach the
Mediterranean, because of tectonic tilting, or
drought in the source regions. The Nile history
has been obtained from sediments in the river
valley which, for times older than the limit of
radiocarbon at about 50 ka, connot at present
be dated. The generally accepted history of
the Nile was worked out by Said, R., 1981, The
geological evolution of the River Nile: New
river Nile: geology, hydrology, and utilization:
Oxford, Pergamon, 320 p., shown here in blue.
Other versions have been given by
here in pink, and by Sampsell, B., 2003, A
traveler's guide to the geology of Egypt: How
the land made Egypt what it is: Cairo/New
York, American University in Cairo Press, 272
p., here in green. The differences do not reflect
different age determinations, but rather reflect
the inability to date the sediments on which
this history is based. These problems are
